# bridget-supervise — keep bridget running without relying on launchd KeepAlive.
#
# Why this exists (measured on Darwin 24.6.0, mg-0655):
#
#   `launchctl print` reports a field called `pended nondemand spawn`. A
#   "nondemand" spawn is any spawn launchd decides to do on its own: RunAtLoad,
#   a KeepAlive restart, or a StartInterval fire. launchd defers those and marks
#   them `inefficient` (or `speculative` at load time). The deferral is not a
#   short delay: a KeepAlive job that took SIGTERM was observed still
#   `state=not running, runs=1` 115 seconds later, and com.pogo.watchdog and
#   com.pogo.gh-issues sat in exactly that state for ~4.8 hours before a human
#   kickstarted them by hand. A *demand* spawn — `launchctl kickstart` — is
#   never pended. (Why they died is a separate, since-fixed bug: unanchored
#   `pkill -f "sleep 600"` from unrelated sessions matched their idle sleep. Why
#   they STAYED dead is this, and it is still open: mg-e701.)
#
#   So `KeepAlive=true` cannot be trusted to restart bridget when bridget exits.
#   Neither can StartInterval (also a nondemand spawn, also pended), and
#   ProcessType=Interactive does not exempt a job either. All three were tested,
#   as was the KeepAlive dict form (mg-50e0, independently).
#
#   The fix that does not depend on launchd's mood: never let the supervised
#   process be the thing launchd has to respawn. This wrapper is what launchd
#   starts, and it stays alive across bridget's crashes, restarting bridget
#   itself. launchd then only has to spawn us once.
#
# What this does NOT fix: if something kills *this wrapper*, restarting it is
# launchd's job, and that restart is subject to the same pending. That residual
# is the open platform fault mg-e701; its fix is a live process issuing
# `launchctl kickstart`, not anything expressible in a plist. See README
# "Running as a service".
#
# Signals: SIGTERM/SIGINT are forwarded to bridget and then honored. We do not
# trap-and-ignore them — `launchctl bootout` and `kickstart -k` must work, and a
# daemon that refuses to die is worse than one that needs a kick.
#
# The target: a long-lived supervisor may only ever supervise a *durable* path.
# BRIDGET_BIN used to be resolved once at startup and exec'd unchanged forever,
# so a supervisor that inherited a path into a polecat worktree kept that path
# after the worktree was deleted. On 2026-07-10, 14:40Z-14:58Z, that is exactly
# what happened: `FATAL: no bridget at ~/.pogo/polecats/0655/bridget`, exit 1,
# KeepAlive respawn, same FATAL, every ThrottleInterval=10 seconds, for 18
# minutes. Nothing noticed. `launchctl list` reported a pid the whole time and
# `pogo doctor --check` stayed green, because both of them ask whether a process
# exists, not whether it works. A human re-pointed the path by hand (mg-1679).
#
# Three defenses. They do different jobs; none of them subsumes another:
#
#   1. Never exec a target under ~/.pogo/polecats/ (symlinks resolved). An
#      ephemeral path is invalid by construction as a long-lived supervisor's
#      target, whoever asked for it. This is the guard that makes the class
#      impossible to enter. What it cannot do is keep us out of the class: it
#      is one check, and a path that is durable at 14:40 is deleted at 14:48.
#   2. Re-check the target before *every* spawn, not once at startup. This is
#      what catches the target vanishing under a running supervisor, or the
#      ~/.pogo/bin/bridget symlink being repointed into a worktree. It is (1)'s
#      blind spot exactly.
#   3. When (1) or (2) rejects the target, fall back to $DEFAULT_BIN and keep
#      supervising. (2) without (3) merely notices the outage. (3) without (2)
#      never gets the chance.
#
# Refusing an ephemeral path and dying are separable, and we do the first
# without the second: with a durable default sitting right there, exiting 1
# would leave bridget down for no benefit anyone can name. The one exception is
# a target that is merely *missing* at startup — nothing is running yet, so
# there is no service to preserve, and a path the operator named that does not
# exist is a mistake to surface, not to paper over.
#
# And whichever of the three fires: SAY SO. A supervisor that will not exec its
# configured target mails the mayor (rate-limited, so a 10s respawn loop is not
# a mail flood) and logs to stderr as well as stdout. The 18-minute outage was
# not caused by the pinned path. It was caused by the pinned path failing where
# nothing was looking.

set -uo pipefail   # deliberately not -e: bridget's nonzero exit is data, not fatal.

# The durable install target: a symlink install.sh drops into the checkout. This
# is the only path a supervisor is entitled to assume outlives it.
DEFAULT_BIN="$HOME/.pogo/bin/bridget"
BRIDGET_BIN="${BRIDGET_BIN:-$DEFAULT_BIN}"

# Where pogo puts its ephemeral polecat worktrees. Anything under here is
# deleted without warning when the polecat that owns it is reaped.
EPHEMERAL_ROOT="$HOME/.pogo/polecats"
# Escape hatch for a polecat smoke-testing its own build: `BRIDGET_ALLOW_
# EPHEMERAL_BIN=1 ./bridget-supervise`. Opt-in and explicit, which is the whole
# point — the outage came from an *inherited* BRIDGET_BIN that nobody chose.
ALLOW_EPHEMERAL="${BRIDGET_ALLOW_EPHEMERAL_BIN:-0}"

# Restart backoff. A bridget that dies instantly (bad token, missing env file)
# must not become a fork bomb; a bridget that dies after a week of uptime must
# not inherit that history and wait 5 minutes to come back.
MIN_BACKOFF="${BRIDGET_MIN_BACKOFF:-5}"
MAX_BACKOFF="${BRIDGET_MAX_BACKOFF:-300}"
# A run at least this long is evidence the config is fine and the exit was
# transient (a dropped gateway socket), so the next restart is immediate-ish.
HEALTHY_RUNTIME="${BRIDGET_HEALTHY_RUNTIME:-60}"
# Test hook: stop after N spawns instead of looping forever. 0 = never stop.
MAX_SPAWNS="${BRIDGET_MAX_SPAWNS:-0}"

# Alerting. `mg mail send` unless overridden; BRIDGET_ALERT_CMD names a program
# invoked as `cmd <subject> <body>` (a program, not a shell string — nothing
# here word-splits a command).
ALERT_TO="${BRIDGET_ALERT_TO:-mayor}"
ALERT_CMD="${BRIDGET_ALERT_CMD:-}"
# launchd respawns us every ThrottleInterval=10s. Alerting on every one of those
# would mail the mayor 360 times an hour, which is its own kind of silence. The
# stamp is on disk because each respawn is a fresh process with no memory of the
# last: an in-process counter would rate-limit nothing.
ALERT_COOLDOWN="${BRIDGET_ALERT_COOLDOWN:-900}"
ALERT_STAMP="${BRIDGET_ALERT_STAMP:-$HOME/.pogo/bridget-supervise.alert}"
# A hung notifier must never keep us from exiting.
ALERT_TIMEOUT="${BRIDGET_ALERT_TIMEOUT:-10}"

log() { printf '[supervise %s] %s\n' "$(date -u '+%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ')" "$*"; }

child=""
sleep_pid=""
notify_pid=""
terminating=0

# Chase symlinks to a physical path. Not `realpath`/`readlink -f`: neither is
# portable to the bash 3.2 + BSD userland this runs on by default.
resolve_path() {
    local p="$1" target dir hops=0
    while [[ -L "$p" ]]; do
        if (( ++hops > 40 )); then   # a symlink cycle; report what we have
            printf '%s\n' "$p"
            return 0
        fi
        target="$(readlink "$p")"
        [[ "$target" == /* ]] || target="$(dirname "$p")/$target"
        p="$target"
    done
    # The leaf need not exist; its directory usually does, and a symlinked
    # directory component is just as capable of pointing into a worktree.
    if dir="$(cd -P -- "$(dirname -- "$p")" 2>/dev/null && pwd -P)"; then
        printf '%s/%s\n' "${dir%/}" "$(basename -- "$p")"
    else
        printf '%s\n' "$p"
    fi
}

# The root resolved too, or the comparison is decided by whether two paths
# happened to be spelled with the same symlinks: on macOS `/var/…/polecats/x`
# and `/private/var/…/polecats/x` are the same file and neither is a prefix of
# the other. Falls back to the literal when the root does not exist yet.
EPHEMERAL_ROOT_REAL="$(resolve_path "$EPHEMERAL_ROOT")"
[[ -n "$EPHEMERAL_ROOT_REAL" ]] || EPHEMERAL_ROOT_REAL="$EPHEMERAL_ROOT"

# Both the literal path and its resolved form: `~/.pogo/polecats/x/bridget` is
# ephemeral even once deleted and no longer resolvable, and `~/.pogo/bin/bridget`
# is ephemeral when the symlink install.sh dropped lands in a worktree.
is_ephemeral() {
    case "$1" in "$EPHEMERAL_ROOT"/*) return 0 ;; esac
    case "$(resolve_path "$1")" in
        "$EPHEMERAL_ROOT"/* | "$EPHEMERAL_ROOT_REAL"/*) return 0 ;;
    esac
    return 1
}

# True when the target is ephemeral and the operator has not said otherwise.
ephemeral_veto() {
    [[ "$ALLOW_EPHEMERAL" == 1 ]] && return 1
    is_ephemeral "$1"
}

runnable() { [[ -x "$1" || -f "$1" ]]; }

# One alert per ALERT_COOLDOWN seconds across every respawn of this script.
alert_due() {
    local now last
    now="$(date +%s)"
    if [[ -r "$ALERT_STAMP" ]]; then
        last="$(cat "$ALERT_STAMP" 2>/dev/null)"
        [[ "$last" =~ ^[0-9]+$ ]] || last=0
        (( now - last < ALERT_COOLDOWN )) && return 1
    fi
    mkdir -p "$(dirname "$ALERT_STAMP")" 2>/dev/null || true
    printf '%s\n' "$now" >"$ALERT_STAMP" 2>/dev/null || true
    return 0
}

notify() {
    local subject="$1" body="$2"
    if [[ -n "$ALERT_CMD" ]]; then
        "$ALERT_CMD" "$subject" "$body" || log "alert command $ALERT_CMD failed"
        return 0
    fi
    if ! command -v mg >/dev/null 2>&1; then
        log "mg is not on PATH; this alert exists only in the log"
        return 0
    fi
    mg mail send "$ALERT_TO" --from=bridget-supervise \
        --subject="$subject" --body="$body" >/dev/null 2>&1 \
        || log "mg mail send to $ALERT_TO failed; this alert exists only in the log"
}

# Loud on both streams: launchd routes them to bridget.log and bridget.err.log,
# and a human tailing the failure of a daemon tails the error log.
alert() {
    local subject="$1" body="$2"
    log "ALERT: $subject — $body"
    log "ALERT: $subject — $body" >&2
    if ! alert_due; then
        log "alert to $ALERT_TO throttled (last one <${ALERT_COOLDOWN}s ago)"
        return 0
    fi
    # Backgrounded so a wedged notifier cannot stall bridget's restart. The
    # FATAL paths drain it before exiting; the recovery path lets it finish
    # while bridget comes back up.
    notify "$subject" "$body" &
    notify_pid=$!
}

drain_alert() {
    [[ -n "$notify_pid" ]] || return 0
    local waited=0
    while kill -0 "$notify_pid" 2>/dev/null && (( waited < ALERT_TIMEOUT )); do
        sleep 1 || true   # bounded; see the `|| true` rationale at the backoff
        waited=$((waited + 1))
    done
    kill -TERM "$notify_pid" 2>/dev/null || true
    notify_pid=""
}

on_signal() {
    local sig="$1"
    terminating=1
    log "got SIG$sig; forwarding to bridget${child:+ (pid $child)} and exiting"
    if [[ -n "$child" ]] && kill -0 "$child" 2>/dev/null; then
        kill -"$sig" "$child" 2>/dev/null || true
        wait "$child" 2>/dev/null || true
    fi
    # We may be mid-backoff. Reap the sleep rather than orphaning it for the
    # remainder of MAX_BACKOFF.
    if [[ -n "$sleep_pid" ]] && kill -0 "$sleep_pid" 2>/dev/null; then
        kill -TERM "$sleep_pid" 2>/dev/null || true
    fi
    if [[ -n "$notify_pid" ]] && kill -0 "$notify_pid" 2>/dev/null; then
        kill -TERM "$notify_pid" 2>/dev/null || true
    fi
    # 128 + signal number, the convention bridget's exit 143 (128+15) follows.
    case "$sig" in
        TERM) exit 143 ;;
        INT)  exit 130 ;;
        *)    exit 1   ;;
    esac
}
trap 'on_signal TERM' TERM
trap 'on_signal INT'  INT

die_loudly() {
    alert "bridget-supervise cannot run bridget" "$1"
    drain_alert
    exit 1
}

# Defenses 1-3. Called once before the loop and again before every spawn, which
# is the whole of defense 2. Returns with BRIDGET_BIN naming something runnable
# and durable, or does not return at all.
#
# `phase` is `startup` or `respawn`, and it decides one thing: whether a target
# that is merely missing may fall back. See the header.
resolve_target() {
    local phase="$1" why="" real=""

    if ephemeral_veto "$BRIDGET_BIN"; then
        # Name the resolved path only when it differs, or a plain path prints as
        # "X resolves to X" and reads like a bug in the thing reporting the bug.
        real="$(resolve_path "$BRIDGET_BIN")"
        if [[ "$real" == "$BRIDGET_BIN" ]]; then
            real=""
        else
            real=" (a symlink to $real)"
        fi
        why="$BRIDGET_BIN$real is under the ephemeral worktree root
$EPHEMERAL_ROOT. That path is deleted when the polecat owning it is reaped, so
it is never a valid target for a supervisor meant to outlive it (mg-1679). To
supervise it anyway: BRIDGET_ALLOW_EPHEMERAL_BIN=1."
    elif ! runnable "$BRIDGET_BIN"; then
        [[ "$phase" == startup ]] && die_loudly \
            "FATAL: no bridget at $BRIDGET_BIN — run install.sh"
        why="$BRIDGET_BIN disappeared while it was being supervised."
    else
        return 0
    fi

    if [[ "$BRIDGET_BIN" != "$DEFAULT_BIN" ]] \
        && runnable "$DEFAULT_BIN" && ! ephemeral_veto "$DEFAULT_BIN"; then
        alert "bridget-supervise fell back to $DEFAULT_BIN" "$why
Falling back to the durable default $DEFAULT_BIN and continuing to supervise.
bridget is up; whatever set BRIDGET_BIN to a path that could not outlive this
supervisor still wants fixing."
        BRIDGET_BIN="$DEFAULT_BIN"
        return 0
    fi

    die_loudly "FATAL: $why
$DEFAULT_BIN is not a usable fallback, so bridget is down and this supervisor
cannot bring it back. Run install.sh."
}

resolve_target startup

backoff="$MIN_BACKOFF"
spawns=0

log "supervising $BRIDGET_BIN (pid $$)"

while true; do
    resolve_target respawn

    started="$SECONDS"
    spawns=$((spawns + 1))
    log "starting bridget (spawn #$spawns)"

    "$BRIDGET_BIN" &
    child=$!
    wait "$child"
    rc=$?
    child=""

    (( terminating )) && break

    ran=$((SECONDS - started))

    if (( ran >= HEALTHY_RUNTIME )); then
        # It held a gateway connection for a while; treat this as a blip.
        backoff="$MIN_BACKOFF"
        log "bridget exited rc=$rc after ${ran}s (healthy run); restarting in ${backoff}s"
    else
        log "bridget exited rc=$rc after ${ran}s (too fast); restarting in ${backoff}s"
    fi

    if (( MAX_SPAWNS > 0 && spawns >= MAX_SPAWNS )); then
        log "reached BRIDGET_MAX_SPAWNS=$MAX_SPAWNS; exiting"
        exit "$rc"
    fi

    # The backoff sleep runs in the *background*, and we `wait` on it. Both
    # halves of that are load-bearing.
    #
    # `wait`, because bash runs a trap only once the current foreground command
    # returns. A plain `sleep "$backoff"` therefore made this wrapper ignore
    # SIGTERM for the rest of the backoff — measured at 2m44s on 2026-07-10
    # (mg-b4f1), against a header comment promising that `launchctl bootout` and
    # `kickstart -k` work. launchd escalates an unanswered SIGTERM to SIGKILL,
    # which kills us mid-backoff and orphans bridget: a live bot with no
    # supervisor, which is the failure this whole script exists to prevent.
    # `wait` *is* interruptible, so the trap fires immediately.
    #
    # `|| true`, because on 2026-07-10 every pogo poller on this host died at
    # once when unanchored `pkill -f "sleep 600"` from unrelated sessions matched
    # their idle `sleep`; the sleep returned 143, `set -e` fired, and each poller
    # killed itself (mg-8c9c, mg-67b5). We do not enable `set -e` above, so this
    # is belt and braces — but a supervisor that someone else's pkill can stop is
    # not a supervisor.
    sleep "$backoff" &
    sleep_pid=$!
    wait "$sleep_pid" || true
    sleep_pid=""

    if (( ran < HEALTHY_RUNTIME )); then
        backoff=$(( backoff * 2 ))
        (( backoff > MAX_BACKOFF )) && backoff="$MAX_BACKOFF"
    fi
done
